## 96 Ways to Mess Up: A Look Into the Most Frequent Offenders
The food recall tally for 2026 has reached 314 events so far, with an alarming 87 marked as Class I recalls--posing the highest level of risk to health. Leading the pack in recall incidents this year is CHETAK NEW YORK LLC with 52 recalls, all Class I. Close behind are Made Fresh Salads Inc and Diva Fam Inc, among others, with several Class I and Class II offenses. It's not just a numbers game; the reasons behind these recalls are equally concerning.

## Recent Recall Highlights
On April 15, a peculiar mix of recalls surfaced. From mislabeled allergens to undeclared pharmaceuticals, the spectrum of issues couldn't be wider: 
- **Zarlengo Italian Ice:** Multiple gelato products were recalled due to undeclared soy allergen despite its presence in the ingredients.
- **Pure Vitamins and Natural Supplements, LLC:** If you picked up anything labeled "Extreme Male Enhancement Supplement," you might have gotten more than you bargained for--undeclared sildenafil and tadalafil were found.
- **MEI YU CHENG DA TRADING INC:** Products containing banned sweetener cyclamates were pulled from shelves. Cyclamates have been prohibited in the U.S. since the 1970s due to potential health risks.

## A Grim Outlook
This year's recall count is on track to break records. With 87 Class I recalls so far, 2026 seems poised to rival 2025's 146 recalls in October alone. While it's easy to get lost in the numbers, each recall represents a breakdown in food safety--a process that should protect us all from harm.

## The Takeaway
From Sweeteners to Allergens: What's a Consumer to Do? Staying informed is paramount. If you're stocking up on any of the aforementioned brands or products, double-check your pantry. Knowledge is the first ingredient in dodging a mishap.
